"# Chapter 6 — Macros and macroexpand: the code before the code

A macro rewrites source before evaluation. You write one form; the macro turns it into another form; the interpreter evaluates that other form. If you cannot see the rewrite, you cannot debug it. This chapter shows how to see the rewrite in Motoi.

## 6.1 Why introspect a macro?

Because macros can bite. A macro can capture a variable you did not know it captured. A macro can generate code that shadows something in your env. A macro can loop forever if you have a bug in its pattern. Every one of these is impossible to debug without seeing the expansion.

Motoi's macro system uses `syntax-rules` with an auto-hygiene layer that gensyms new bindings. This means most macros are safe by default. But *most* is not *all*, and even hygienic macros produce forms you should be able to see.

## 6.2 The two verbs

- `macroexpand form` — fully expand a form, showing what the interpreter will actually evaluate.
- `macroexpand-1 form` — do one step of expansion, so you can walk through nested macros one at a time.

```scheme
(macroexpand '(when (> x 0) (display x) (newline)))
;; => (if (> x 0) (begin (display x) (newline)))
```

The `when` macro expanded into an `if` wrapping a `begin`. Now you know what the interpreter sees.

```scheme
(macroexpand-1 '(unless (< x 0) (display x)))
;; => (if (not (< x 0)) (display x))
```

One step. `unless` becomes `if` + `not`. If `unless` expanded to something that itself contained macros, `macroexpand-1` would stop after one step; `macroexpand` would keep going.

## 6.3 The REPL shortcut

```
> ,expand (when (> x 0) (display x))
{... JSON of the expanded form ...}
```

See `src/repl.js` line 99 for the meta-command dispatch. It calls `expandProgram` from `src/macro.js` and prints the JSON of the result.

