## 6.17 A worked example — debugging a broken macro

You write a macro. It errors when you use it. You do not know why.

```scheme
(define-syntax swap!
  (syntax-rules ()
    ((_ a b)
     (let ((tmp a))
       (set! a b)
       (set! b tmp)))))

(swap! x y)  ;; error
```

Why does it error? Expand to see:

```scheme
(macroexpand '(swap! x y))
;; => (let ((tmp x)) (set! x y) (set! y tmp))
```

Read the expansion. `tmp` is introduced in the let. If the caller has a `tmp` in scope, there is a shadowing. If `set!` is failing on x or y, one of them is not bindable. Either way, the expansion tells you.

For most bugs, `macroexpand` is 90% of the debug. Read the expansion. The bug is usually visible in the shape.

